<TITLE> Islamist campaigners in Sylhet demand scrapping of women's policy </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 4 (bdnews24.com)Dozens of people were injured Friday after police teargassed thousands of madrasa students and teachers who took to the streets in Sylhet city with calls for scrapping of the National Women's Development Policy. The chaos turned violent as security officials intercepted the protesters in Zindabazar area as they held a rally violating emergency rules. The protesters under the banner of Quranic Law Protection Committee gathered in the city, with many coming from outlying areas. They also demanded resignation of women and children affairs adviser Rasheda K Choudhury. Two seriously injured protesters were taken to Sylhet Osmani Medical College Hospital. The police briefly detained three madrasa students. Security has been tightened in the northeastern city. The protesters said the police used rubber bullets along with teargas, but Sylhet Metropolitan Police's additional commissioner Israil Hawlader denied the use of rubber bullets. The protesters later announced a door-to-door campaign for April 7-17, simultaneous processions in all upazilas of Sylhet on April 23 and a rally on April 24 in Sylhet city. Meanwhile, similar protests occurred in Chittagong city but there were no reports of violence. Many protesters under Ahkame Sharia Hefajat Committee marched through the city streets. At a rally on the premises of Anderkilla Shahi Jame Mosque, the protesters demanded immediate withdrawal of the women's development policy, terming it anti-Islamic. bdnews24.co
